  <p>
    Here are the seven signals worth knowing, roughly in the order they tend to
    appear — from "keep an eye on it" to "stop and call someone today."
  </p>

  <h2>1. Drains getting slower throughout the house</h2>
  <p>
    One slow sink is a clog in that fixture. <strong>Every</strong> drain slowing
    down — sinks, shower, toilets — points at the system they all share. If
    plunging and drain cleaner keep "fixing" it for a week at a time, the problem
    isn't in the pipe.
  </p>

  <h2>2. Gurgling pipes</h2>
  <p>
    That bubbling sound when a toilet flushes or a bath drains is air being
    pushed back through the system because waste isn't moving freely. It's one of
    the earliest and most commonly ignored warnings.
  </p>

  <h2>3. Sewage odors</h2>
  <p>
    A rotten-egg smell indoors near drains, or outdoors around the tank and drain
    field, means gas is escaping where it shouldn't. Indoors it can be a dried-out
    trap or a venting issue; outdoors it usually points at the tank itself.
    Persistent odor is also a sign the tank's aerobic bacteria are losing to the
    anaerobic ones — the condition a good treatment is designed to correct.
  </p>

  <h2>4. Unusually lush, green grass over the drain field</h2>
  <p>
    A bright green stripe in an otherwise ordinary lawn looks like good luck. It
    isn't. It means effluent is surfacing and fertilizing that patch, which is a
    sign the field isn't absorbing properly.
  </p>

  <h2>5. Soggy ground or standing water near the tank or field</h2>
  <p>
    Wet ground with no rain to explain it means liquid is escaping the system.
    This is a genuine "call a professional" symptom — at this point the drain
    field is already struggling, and continuing to load it makes the repair
    bigger.
  </p>

  <h2>6. Sewage backing up into the house</h2>
  <p>
    The unambiguous emergency. Backup — usually in the lowest drains first —
    means the system has nowhere to send waste. Stop using water, and get a
    professional out the same day. Every additional flush makes the cleanup worse.
  </p>

  <h2>7. Bacteria or nitrates in your well water</h2>
  <p>
    If you're on a private well, an annual water test is the quietest early
    warning available. Rising nitrates or any coliform bacteria can indicate
    septic effluent reaching groundwater — a health issue, not just a plumbing
    one. Test yearly regardless of whether anything seems wrong.
  </p>

  <h2>What to do about each</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Signs 1–3</strong> — get the tank inspected and pumped if you're near or past due, and get consistent bacterial maintenance going. Often that's the whole fix.</li>
    <li><strong>Signs 4–5</strong> — professional inspection. The tank may just need pumping, but the field needs assessing before you keep loading it.</li>
    <li><strong>Sign 6</strong> — stop water use, call a professional immediately.</li>
    <li><strong>Sign 7</strong> — retest to confirm, then have the system inspected; don't drink the water until it's clear.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Most of this is preventable</h2>
  <p>
    The great majority of septic failures trace back to two things: going too
    long between pump-outs, and letting the tank's bacteria die off so solids
    build faster than they should. Both are cheap to stay ahead of. Work out your
    real pumping interval with our guide to
    <a href="/blog/how-often-pump-septic-tank/">how often to pump a septic tank</a>,
    keep grease and non-degradables out, and run a consistent bacterial treatment
    — we compare the ones worth using in our
    <a href="/reviews/best-septic-tank-treatments/">best septic tank treatments guide</a>.
  </p>
  <p>
    A septic system that's maintained is close to invisible. That's the goal:
    never having to think about it.
  </p>
